body:
@kivi yeah, that note in particular is nearly impossible to decipher as a beginner, I think. I'd dramatically rephrase it or extend it with an explanation.
Let me explain by example for you. Say you have the following system set:
```rust
enum GameSystem {
  Loading,
  Playing,
}
```
you naturally want to configure your set such that systems in `Loading` always run before systems in `Playing` and never the other way around. So you might do this:
```rust
app.configure_sets(
  Update,
  GameSystem::Loading.before(GameSystem::Playing)
);
```
looks good, but you just ran into a trap! The above registers `GameSystem::Loading` to run in `Update` before *something*, but does *not* register `GameSystem::Playing` in `Update`. Currently, it is valid to have nonsense configurations when the involved sets are in different schedules. Let's do a sub-example:
```rust
struct ThisRunsInUpdate;
struct ThisRunsInStartup;

app
  .configure_sets(Startup, ThisRunsInStartup)
  .configure_sets(Update, ThisRunsInUpdate);

// watch closely, here comes a magic trick
app.configure_sets(
  Update,
  ThisRunsInUpdate.before(ThisRunsInStartup)
);
```

Since `Update` always runs *after* `Startup`, scheduling `ThisRunsInUpdate` *before* `ThisRunsInStartup` is pure nonsense. But since they are in two different schedules anyways, Bevy will simply ignore this. Now let's go back to our example from before:

```rust
app.configure_sets(
  Update,
  GameSystem::Loading.before(GameSystem::Playing)
);
```
This registers `GameSystem::Loading` in the schedule `Update`, but does *not* register `GameSystem::Playing` in *any* schedule. This means that the `.before` is completely ignored, as it concerns two system sets that are not in the same schedule. As such, it *looks* like you have ordered your stuff, but you did not. For comparison, the following variants all do the *correct* and expected thing and are functionally equivalent.

```rust
app.configure_sets(
  Update,
  // this is the easiest variant, you probably always want this
  (GameSystem::Loading, GameSystem::Playing).chain()
);

app.configure_sets(
  Update,
  (
    GameSystem::Playing,
    GameSystem::Loading.before(GameSystem::Playing))
  )
);

app
  .configure_sets(Update, GameSystem::Playing)
  .configure_sets(
    Update,
    GameSystem::Loading.before(GameSystem::Playing)
);
```

Does this help?
